That’s a grounded way to approach it.

You’re not arguing about whether heaven or hell are metaphysically real.

You’re shifting the control surface.

Whether ultimate destinations exist or not, the only domain of agency is the present moment.

That’s not theology.
That’s time mechanics.

⸻

1️⃣ The Now as Control Surface

You cannot:
	•	Change the past.
	•	Directly experience the future.
	•	Verify post-mortem states.

But you can:
	•	Adjust perception.
	•	Adjust action.
	•	Adjust response.

So from an operational standpoint, the present is the only lever.

This is why so many traditions converge on similar advice:
	•	Mindfulness (Buddhism)
	•	“Take no thought for tomorrow” (Christian texts)
	•	Stoic present discipline (Marcus Aurelius)
	•	Samurai immediacy
	•	Even SEAL training — task focus, breath, next step

Different metaphysics. Same behavioral optimization.

⸻

2️⃣ Heaven and Hell as State Models

There’s another layer.

Heaven and hell don’t only function as future destinations.
They function as psychological states.

You can:
	•	Experience guilt, shame, anxiety → hell-like state.
	•	Experience alignment, coherence, connection → heaven-like state.

Right now.

So even if metaphysical heaven exists,
your lived experience is mediated through the present nervous system.

⸻

3️⃣ The Paradox

You say:

Now is under your control.

Partially true.

But even the present includes:
	•	Conditioning
	•	Biology
	•	Emotional residue
	•	Environmental pressure

So control is not absolute.
It’s influence within constraint.

That makes the present less mystical —
and more disciplined.

⸻

4️⃣ Why This Framing Is Stable

If heaven/hell exist →
Living well now aligns you anyway.

If they don’t exist →
Living well now is still optimal.

So the present-focused ethic is robust across metaphysical uncertainty.

That’s actually a very stable philosophy.

⸻

Now I’ll ask you something simple and non-provocative:

When you say “now is under your control,”
do you mean emotional regulation, moral action, or narrative framing?